{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9da444f9994a67d0", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tSimple Features and Honest Calibration for Ambivalence and Hesitancy Recognition in Video\n2\tReport GitHub Issue\n3\t×\n4\tTitle:\n5\tContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\n6\tDescription:\n7\tSubmit without GitHub\n8\tSubmit in GitHub\n9\tarXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\n10\tLearn more\n11\t×\n12\tBack to arXiv\n13\tLicense: CC BY 4.0\n14\tarXiv:2607.11120v1 [cs.CV] 13 Jul 2026\n15\tSimple Features and Honest Calibration for\n16\tAmbivalence and Hesitancy Recognition in Video\n17\tVikas Kumar\n18\tIndian Institute of Science Education and Research Bhopal, India\n19\tvikas25@iiserb.ac.in\n20\tAditya Mishra\n21\tIndian Institute of Science Education and Research Bhopal, India\n22\taditya21@iiserb.ac.in\n23\tHaroon R. Lone\n24\tIndian Institute of Science Education and Research Bhopal, India\n25\tharoon@iiserb.ac.in\n26\tAbstract\n27\tWe address ambivalence and hesitancy (A/H) recognition in the ABAW 2026 BAH\n28\tChallenge: given a short interview video, predict whether the person shows signs\n29\tof A/H. Our system combines affect-specialised text, audio, and visual\n30\trepresentations with a small set of readable linguistic hesitation cues, fused by\n31\ta reliability gate we call Affective Marker Fusion (AMF), and finished with a\n32\tsimple AP-weighted ensemble at a fixed decision threshold. We also introduce\n33\tASR-erased time\n34\t: speech recognisers delete fillers and hesitation pauses\n35\tfrom the transcript, but the chunk timestamps keep the time those events took, and\n36\tsixteen features built from these gaps form the strongest and most independent\n37\tnon-verbal channel we measured (AP\n38\t0.718\n39\t0.718\n40\t, correlation\n41\t0.11\n42\t0.11\n43\t–\n44\t0.36\n45\t0.36\n46\twith all\n47\tother members). Across controlled experiments we find three things: cross-modal\n48\tconflict design does not reliably help on BAH; language is by far the strongest\n49\tchannel while affect-specialised audio is a useful second; and calibration matters\n50\tmore than architecture. Fitting ensemble weights and a threshold on the small validation split overfits: it scores\n51\t0.741\n52\t0.741\n53\tmacro-F1 on validation but only\n54\t0.690\n55\t0.690\n56\ton the untouched test set. AP-weighting at a fixed threshold instead reaches\n57\t0.731\n58\t\\mathbf{0.731}\n59\ton test.\n60\tThe full pipeline is deterministic and runs from one script.\n61\t1\n62\t1\n63\t1\n64\tCode:\n65\thttps://github.com/wmivikas/ABAW2026-Task2-ECCV\n66\t.\n67\t1\n68\tIntroduction\n69\tAmbivalence and hesitancy (A/H) are states of internal conflict: a person is unsure,\n70\tor pulled two ways at once. Detecting these moments in short answer videos is useful\n71\tfor behaviour-change tools, where a moment of hesitation is a good time to\n72\tintervene. The ABAW 2026 challenge frames this as a binary, video-level task on the\n73\tBAH dataset\n74\t[\n75\t6\n76\t]\n77\t, scored by macro-F1 (the unweighted mean of the\n78\tpresent- and absent-class F1) with average precision (AP) as a secondary measure.\n79\tA/H is widely treated as a\n80\tcross-modal conflict\n81\tproblem, and the strongest\n82\tprior systems build hand-designed conflict features on top of three pre-trained\n83\tencoders\n84\t[\n85\t2\n86\t,\n87\t18\n88\t]\n89\t. We reproduce that\n90\trecipe, test its central claim, and then ask a simpler question: where is the signal\n91\tactually? Three results organise the paper.\n92\t1.\n93\tConflict design is not the lever.\n94\tWith encoders and training fixed,\n95\tswapping the conflict operator (absolute difference, orthogonal split, or none)\n96\tmoves public-test AP by at most\n97\t0.05\n98\t0.05\n99\tand does not order the same way on validation\n100\tand test (Sec.\n101\t4.5\n102\t).\n103\t2.\n104\tFeatures help, but narrowly.\n105\tWith general encoders the video and audio\n106\tchannels are near chance. An emotion-specialised audio encoder is a real gain; no\n107\tfacial representation we tried rescues the video channel (Sec.\n108\t4.4\n109\t).\n110\tCalibration is the biggest gain.\n111\tOn\n112\t778\n113\t778\n114\ttraining videos, fitting ensemble weights and the decision threshold on the\n115\t124\n116\t124\n117\t-video validation split scores\n118\t0.741\n119\t0.741\n120\tthere but only\n121\t0.690\n122\t0.690\n123\ton test — the classic overfitting signature. Removing that search and using AP weights at a fixed threshold lifts public-test macro-F1 to\n124\t0.731\n125\t0.731\n126\t(Sec.\n127\t4.6\n128\t).\n129\tContributions.\n130\t•\n131\tAMF\n132\t, a compact reliability-gated fusion of affect-specialised streams\n133\tand eleven interpretable hesitation markers.\n134\t•\n135\tASR-erased time\n136\t, a new\n137\t16\n138\t16\n139\t-dimensional signal recovered from ASR\n140\tchunk timestamps; it is the strongest non-verbal channel on BAH and nearly\n141\tuncorrelated with every model member.\n142\t•\n143\tA controlled study showing that conflict design does not help, that the signal\n144\tis concentrated in language, and that AP-weighted calibration at a fixed threshold\n145\tis the single largest source of improvement.\n146\t•\n147\tA deterministic, one-command pipeline that reaches\n148\t0.731\n149\t0.731\n150\tmacro-F1 on the\n151\tpublic test, above the previous edition’s winner.\n152\tFigure 1:\n153\tOverview. Text, video, and audio inputs are turned into affect-specialised\n154\tfeatures. AMF gates weak channels and predicts A/H. Six members are combined by\n155\tAP-weighted averaging at a fixed threshold of\n156\t0.5\n157\t0.5\n158\t. Features that hurt the model\n159\t(gaze/brow dynamics, prosody, cue supervision) are excluded.\n160\t2\n161\tRelated Work\n162\tABAW and BAH.\n163\tThe ABAW series benchmarks multimodal affect in\n164\tvideo\n165\t[\n166\t10\n167\t]\n168\t. BAH\n169\t[\n170\t6\n171\t]\n172\tadds whole-video A/H labels\n173\twith transcripts, aligned faces, and per-segment cue tags. The organisers’ zero-shot\n174\tLLM baseline reaches\n175\t0.283\n176\t0.283\n177\tmacro-F1 and their co-attention baseline\n178\t0.59\n179\t0.59\n180\t; the\n181\tprevious edition’s winner reports\n182\t0.694\n183\t0.694\n184\tpublic /\n185\t0.715\n186\t0.715\n187\tprivate\n188\t[\n189\t2\n190\t]\n191\t.\n192\tConflict fusion.\n193\tPrior A/H systems encode conflict as element-wise\n194\tabsolute differences between encoder features\n195\t[\n196\t2\n197\t]\n198\t, echoing\n199\tdisagreement-aware fusion in multimodal sentiment analysis\n200\t[\n201\t16\n202\t]\n203\tand cross-modal mismatch modelling in deception\n204\tdetection\n205\t[\n206\t15\n207\t]\n208\t. We ask whether this helps once the\n209\tencoders are fixed, and find it does not reliably help on BAH.\n210\tGeneral vs. affect-specialised encoders.\n211\tPrior work uses VideoMAE,\n212\tpre-trained for actions\n213\t[\n214\t20\n215\t]\n216\t, and HuBERT, general\n217\tspeech\n218\t[\n219\t9\n220\t]\n221\t. Neither targets facial or vocal emotion. We substitute a\n222\tfacial-expression model and an emotion speech model\n223\t[\n224\t21\n225\t]\n226\t; only the\n227\taudio substitution pays off. For text we use RoBERTa\n228\t[\n229\t11\n230\t]\n231\tfine-tuned on\n232\tGoEmotions\n233\t[\n234\t3\n235\t]\n236\t, whose emotion labels (confusion,\n237\tnervousness) fit hesitancy; a larger general model (DeBERTa-v3-large\n238\t[\n239\t8\n240\t]\n241\t)\n242\twas worse, so the right pre-training beats scale.\n243\tInterpretable hesitation cues.\n244\tHesitancy has well-studied linguistic\n245\tcorrelates: hedges, filled pauses, self-repairs, contrastive markers. We compile\n246\tthese into a short, readable vector that rivals a fine-tuned language model.\n247\tCalibration on small data.\n248\tWith\n249\t778\n250\t778\n251\ttraining videos the macro-F1\n252\tthreshold is high-variance; poor calibration is a known failure mode of modern\n253\tnetworks\n254\t[\n255\t7\n256\t]\n257\t. We show that tuning the threshold on the\n258\t124\n259\t124\n260\t-video validation split does not transfer, and instead fix it and weight members\n261\tby AP, which is threshold-free.\n262\t3\n263\tMethod\n264\t3.1\n265\tProblem formulation\n266\tEach video\n267\tx\n268\tx\n269\thas a binary label\n270\ty\n271\t∈\n272\t{\n273\t0\n274\t,\n275\t1\n276\t}\n277\ty\\in\\{0,1\\}\n278\tand an elicitation question\n279\tq\n280\t∈\n281\t{\n282\t1\n283\t,\n284\t…\n285\t,\n286\t7\n287\t}\n288\tq\\in\\{1,\\dots,7\\}\n289\t. We predict a probability\n290\tp\n291\t​\n292\t(\n293\ty\n294\t=\n295\t1\n296\t∣\n297\tx\n298\t)\n299\tp(y{=}1\\mid x)\n300\tand are scored by\n301\tmacro-F1\n302\t=\n303\t1\n304\t2\n305\t​\n306\t(\n307\tF\n308\t1\n309\t(\n310\t0\n311\t)\n312\t+\n313\tF\n314\t1\n315\t(\n316\t1\n317\t)\n318\t)\n319\t\\text{macro-F1}=\\tfrac{1}{2}(F_{1}^{(0)}+F_{1}^{(1)})\n320\t, with positive-class AP as a\n321\tsecondary measure.\n322\t3.2\n323\tModality encoders\n324\tWe use frozen affect-oriented encoders (Table\n325\t1\n326\t). Text is the\n327\tRoBERTa-GoEmotions sentence embedding; video is a facial-expression ViT\n328\t[\n329\t4\n330\t]\n331\tover\n332\t16\n333\t16\n334\taligned face frames, giving an embedding and a\n335\t7\n336\t7\n337\t-way expression profile\n338\t(mean and standard deviation); audio is an emotion-fine-tuned\n339\twav2vec2\n340\t[\n341\t1\n342\t]\n343\tmodel\n344\t[\n345\t21\n346\t]\n347\t, mean-pooled over time. We additionally compute eleven interpretable text markers: rates of hedges,\n348\tfilled pauses, contrastive (“but”-type) words, negations, first-person uncertainty,\n349\trepeated words, and how much sentiment flips within the answer.\n350\tTable 1:\n351\tEncoders. All are frozen; only lightweight heads are trained.\n352\tStream\n353\tBackbone\n354\tDim\n355\tText\n356\tRoBERTa-GoEmotions\n357\t[\n358\t3\n359\t]\n360\t768\n361\tText markers\n362\thand-crafted hesitation cues\n363\t11\n364\tVideo\n365\tFER-ViT (facial expression)\n366\t768 + 14\n367\tAudio\n368\temotion wav2vec2\n369\t[\n370\t21\n371\t]\n372\t1024\n373\tEncoder members (separate) also use:\n374\tVideo (enc.)\n375\tVideoMAE-Base\n376\t[\n377\t20\n378\t]\n379\t768\n380\tAudio (enc.)\n381\tHuBERT-Large\n382\t[\n383\t9\n384\t]\n385\t1024\n386\t3.3\n387\tAffective Marker Fusion (AMF)\n388\tEach stream\n389\ts\n390\t∈\n391\t{\n392\ttext\n393\t,\n394\tvideo\n395\t,\n396\taudio\n397\t,\n398\tmarkers\n399\t}\n400\ts\\in\\{\\text{text},\\text{video},\\text{audio},\\text{markers}\\}\n401\tis\n402\tprojected to a shared width,\n403\th\n404\ts\n405\t=\n406\tϕ\n407\ts\n408\t​\n409\t(\n410\tf\n411\ts\n412\t)\n413\th_{s}=\\phi_{s}(f_{s})\n414\t. A learned gate assigns each stream a\n415\treliability weight, so weak channels are turned down rather than added as noise:\n416\tg\n417\t=\n418\tσ\n419\t​\n420\t(\n421\tW\n422\t​\n423\t[\n424\th\n425\tt\n426\t;\n427\th\n428\tv\n429\t;\n430\th\n431\ta\n432\t;\n433\th\n434\tm\n435\t]\n436\t)\n437\t∈\n438\t(\n439\t0\n440\t,\n441\t1\n442\t)\n443\t4\n444\t,\n445\th\n446\t~\n447\ts\n448\t=\n449\tg\n450\ts\n451\t​\n452\th\n453\ts\n454\t.\n455\tg=\\sigma\\!\\big(W[h_{\\text{t}};h_{\\text{v}};h_{\\text{a}};h_{\\text{m}}]\\big)\\in(0,1)^{4},\\qquad\\tilde{h}_{s}=g_{s}\\,h_{s}.\n456\t(1)\n457\tThe gated streams and a question embedding are concatenated and passed to a small\n458\tMLP. An auxiliary head predicts A/H from the markers alone, which regularises the\n459\tshared representation and exposes an interpretable sub-decision. We minimise a class-balanced binary cross-entropy loss with label smoothing,\n460\tℒ\n461\t=\n462\tBCE\n463\t​\n464\tw\n465\t​\n466\t(\n467\tp\n468\t,\n469\ty\n470\t~\n471\t)\n472\t+\n473\t0.3\n474\t⋅\n475\tBCE\n476\t​\n477\tw\n478\t​\n479\t(\n480\tp\n481\t​\n482\tmarker\n483\t,\n484\ty\n485\t)\n486\t,\n487\t\\mathcal{L}=\\mathrm{BCE}w\\big(p,\\tilde{y}\\big)+0.3\\cdot\\mathrm{BCE}w\\big(p{\\text{marker}},y\\big),\n488\t(2)\n489\twhere\n490\tBCE\n491\t​\n492\tw\n493\t​\n494\t(\n495\tp\n496\t,\n497\ty\n498\t)\n499\t=\n500\t−\n501\t,\n502\tw\n503\t,\n504\ty\n505\t​\n506\tlog\n507\t⁡\n508\tp\n509\t−\n510\t(\n511\t1\n512\t−\n513\ty\n514\t)\n515\t​\n516\tlog\n517\t⁡\n518\t(\n519\t1\n520\t−\n521\tp\n522\t)\n523\t\\mathrm{BCE}w(p,y)=-,w,y\\log p-(1-y)\\log(1-p)\n524\t,\n525\tw\n526\t=\n527\t(\n528\tN\n529\t−\n530\tN\n531\t+\n532\t)\n533\t/\n534\tN\n535\t+\n536\tw=(N{-}N{+})/N{+}\n537\tre-weights the positive class by its inverse frequency, and\n538\ty\n539\t~\n540\t=\n541\ty\n542\t​\n543\t(\n544\t1\n545\t−\n546\tϵ\n547\t)\n548\t+\n549\tϵ\n550\t/\n551\t2\n552\t\\tilde{y}=y(1-\\epsilon)+\\epsilon/2\n553\tis the smoothed label (\n554\tϵ\n555\t=\n556\t0.1\n557\t\\epsilon=0.1\n558\t). We use the standard smoothing value\n559\t[\n560\t19\n561\t]\n562\trather than tuning it, since\n563\t778\n564\t778\n565\ttraining videos and noisy labels are exactly the setting label smoothing is meant to guard against overconfidence in. The marker-head weight of\n566\t0.3\n567\t0.3\n568\tis kept low enough that this auxiliary loss regularises the shared representation without dominating the main objective, while still forcing the\n569\t25\n570\t25\n571\t-dim marker pathway to stay independently predictive.\n572\t3.4\n573\tASR-erased time\n574\tSpeech recognisers are trained to output\n575\tclean\n576\ttext: they delete fillers\n577\t(“um”, “uh”), restarts, and hesitation pauses. In BAH, only\n578\t7\n579\t%\n580\t7\\%\n581\tof the Whisper\n582\t[\n583\t17\n584\t]\n585\ttranscripts contain any filler word. But the transcripts carry per-chunk timestamps,\n586\tand time cannot be deleted: when the recogniser drops a filled pause, the gap it\n587\toccupied remains between the end of one chunk and the start of the next. We recover\n588\tsixteen deterministic features from these gaps: gap counts and sizes normalised by\n589\tspeech time, within-chunk speaking rate and its variability, chunk fragmentation,\n590\tthe gap immediately before a contrast word (the pause-then-qualify pattern), and\n591\trestarts across chunk borders. Whisper timestamps reset every\n592\t30\n593\t30\n594\ts, so gaps are\n595\tcounted only where the timeline is monotone.\n596\t3.5\n597\tEnsemble and calibration\n598\tWe combine\n599\tM\n600\tM\n601\tmembers by AP-weighted probability averaging and a\n602\tfixed\n603\tthreshold\n604\tτ\n605\t=\n606\t0.5\n607\t\\tau=0.5\n608\t:\n609\tp\n610\t¯\n611\t​\n612\t(\n613\tx\n614\t)\n615\t=\n616\t∑\n617\tm\n618\tw\n619\tm\n620\t​\n621\tp\n622\tm\n623\t​\n624\t(\n625\tx\n626\t)\n627\t,\n628\tw\n629\tm\n630\t=\n631\tAP\n632\tm\n633\t∑\n634\tm\n635\t′\n636\tAP\n637\tm\n638\t′\n639\t.\n640\t\\bar{p}(x)=\\sum_{m}w_{m}\\,p_{m}(x),\\qquad w_{m}=\\frac{\\mathrm{AP}_{m}}{\\sum_{m^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{AP}_{m^{\\prime}}}.\n641\t(3)\n642\tAP is threshold-free and therefore stable on small data. Fixing\n643\tτ\n644\t\\tau\n645\tis deliberate:\n646\tSec.\n647\t4.6\n648\tshows a validation-tuned threshold does not transfer.\n649\t3.6\n650\tTraining on all labelled data\n651\tThe rules permit training on all labelled data, and with only\n652\t778\n653\t778\n654\ttraining videos to begin with, using the additional val/test videos should only help the final model. For the final model we pool train+val+test (\n655\t1427\n656\t1427\n657\tvideos). Since no split remains for early stopping, we carve a seeded stratified holdout of\n658\t113\n659\t113\n660\tvideos (\n661\t8\n662\t%\n663\t8\\%\n664\t) — chosen to match the proportion of the original validation split (\n665\t124\n666\t/\n667\t1427\n668\t≈\n669\t8.7\n670\t%\n671\t124/1427\\approx 8.7\\%\n672\t), so the stopping signal is exactly as reliable as before while training sees far more data. We fit the ensemble weights on this holdout and keep\n673\tτ\n674\t=\n675\t0.5\n676\t\\tau=0.5\n677\t, the same fixed, untuned threshold justified in Sec.\n678\t4.6\n679\t. Two invariants keep this clean, both enforced in code: every member holds out the\n680\tsame\n681\t113\n682\t113\n683\tvideos from one shared function, so no member is scored on a video it trained on; and the training and inference paths are asserted to return identical probabilities for a saved checkpoint.\n684\t4\n685\tExperiments\n686\t4.1\n687\tDataset\n688\tBAH\n689\t[\n690\t6\n691\t]\n692\tcontains\n693\t1427\n694\t1427\n695\tlabelled videos from\n696\t300\n697\t300\n698\tparticipants,\n699\tsplit participant-wise (Table\n700\t2\n701\t); no person appears in two splits. There\n702\tis also a private test of\n703\t152\n704\t152\n705\tvideos from\n706\t30\n707\t30\n708\tfurther participants, released\n709\tunlabelled: we predict on it but cannot score it, and the organisers rank the\n710\tsubmitted files (up to five trials). Every number we report is measured on the\n711\tlabelled public test (\n712\t525\n713\t525\n714\tvideos, for models trained on the training split) or on\n715\tthe shared\n716\t113\n717\t113\n718\t-video holdout (for the all-data models); we never mix the two.\n719\tTable 2:\n720\tBAH split statistics (participant-wise).\n721\tSplit\n722\tVideos\n723\tA/H (+)\n724\tNo A/H (\n725\t−\n726\t-\n727\t)\n728\tTrain\n729\t778\n730\t385 (49%)\n731\t393 (51%)\n732\tValidation\n733\t124\n734\t75 (60%)\n735\t49 (40%)\n736\tPublic test\n737\t525\n738\t318 (61%)\n739\t207 (39%)\n740\tPrivate test\n741\t152\n742\t—\n743\t—\n744\t4.2\n745\tImplementation details\n746\tAll models are trained on a single NVIDIA RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell Workstation Edition GPU. The encoders are frozen, and lightweight heads are optimized using AdamW\n747\t[\n748\t12\n749\t]\n750\t, label smoothing\n751\t[\n752\t19\n753\t]\n754\t0.1\n755\t0.1\n756\t, and early stopping (patience\n757\t15\n758\t15\n759\t). The\n760\ttext head uses learning rate\n761\t2\n762\t×\n763\t10\n764\t−\n765\t5\n766\t2\\!\\times\\!10^{-5}\n767\tand R-Drop\n768\t[\n769\t23\n770\t]\n771\t; the\n772\tvideo, audio, and fusion heads use\n773\t1\n774\t×\n775\t10\n776\t−\n777\t4\n778\t1\\!\\times\\!10^{-4}\n779\t; AMF uses a shared width of\n780\t256\n781\t256\n782\tand marker-head weight\n783\t0.3\n784\t0.3\n785\t. We implement everything in\n786\tPyTorch\n787\t[\n788\t14\n789\t]\n790\twith the Transformers library\n791\t[\n792\t22\n793\t]\n794\t. Ensemble weights come from Eq.\n795\t3\n796\tand the\n797\tthreshold is fixed at\n798\t0.5\n799\t0.5\n800\t. Training is deterministic within a fixed\n801\tsoftware/hardware state; across sessions individual members can drift by up to about\n802\ta point of F1 (GPU numerics), while the ensemble is stable to\n803\t±\n804\t0.0001\n805\t\\pm 0.0001\n806\t.\n807\t4.3\n808\tMain results\n809\tTable\n810\t3\n811\tcompares our system with published BAH results. A single AMF\n812\tmember already exceeds the strongest BAH baseline, and the AP-weighted six-member\n813\tensemble reaches\n814\t0.731\n815\t0.731\n816\tmacro-F1 on the public test, above the previous edition’s\n817\twinner (\n818\t0.694\n819\t0.694\n820\t). A paired bootstrap over the\n821\t525\n822\t525\n823\ttest videos gives a\n824\t95\n825\t%\n826\t95\\%\n827\tinterval of\n828\t[\n829\t0.693\n830\t,\n831\t0.770\n832\t]\n833\t[0.693,0.770]\n834\tand\n835\tP\n836\t​\n837\t(\n838\tours\n839\t>\n840\t0.694\n841\t)\n842\t=\n843\t0.97\n844\tP(\\text{ours}>0.694)=0.97\n845\t.\n846\tTable 3:\n847\tPublic-test comparison (\n848\t525\n849\t525\n850\tvideos). Baselines from\n851\t[\n852\t6\n853\t]\n854\t;\n855\tprevious winner from\n856\t[\n857\t2\n858\t]\n859\t.\n860\tMethod\n861\tMacro-F1\n862\tZero-shot M-LLM (vision only)\n863\t[\n864\t6\n865\t]\n866\t0.283\n867\tLFAN co-attention (V+A+T)\n868\t[\n869\t6\n870\t]\n871\t0.590\n872\tZero-shot M-LLM + transcript\n873\t[\n874\t6\n875\t]\n876\t0.634\n877\tConflictAwareAH\n878\t[\n879\t2\n880\t]\n881\t0.694\n882\tOurs: AMF single member\n883\t0.725\n884\tOurs: 6-member AP-weighted ensemble\n885\t0.731\n886\t4.4\n887\tWhere the signal is?\n888\tWe fit a logistic probe on each frozen feature stream, all at a fixed threshold of\n889\t0.5\n890\t0.5\n891\t(Table\n892\t4\n893\t). Text is strongest (AP\n894\t0.811\n895\t0.811\n896\t), and eleven\n897\thesitation markers nearly match it (AP\n898\t0.800\n899\t0.800\n900\t). The emotion audio encoder is far\n901\tabove general HuBERT (AP\n902\t0.764\n903\t0.764\n904\tvs.\n905\t0.606\n906\t0.606\n907\t; frozen HuBERT collapses to one class\n908\tat\n909\tτ\n910\t=\n911\t0.5\n912\t\\tau=0.5\n913\t). ASR-erased time reaches AP\n914\t0.718\n915\t0.718\n916\t— above every face and\n917\tgeneral-audio feature — and its predictions correlate only\n918\t0.11\n919\t0.11\n920\t–\n921\t0.36\n922\t0.36\n923\twith the\n924\tsix model members, far below anything else we measured. Every visual representation\n925\tstays weak, including purpose-built gaze/brow dynamics.\n926\tTable 4:\n927\tPer-stream logistic probe, fixed threshold\n928\t0.5\n929\t0.5\n930\t.\n931\tFeature stream\n932\tVal F1\n933\tTest F1\n934\tTest AP\n935\tText: RoBERTa-GoEmotions (768)\n936\t0.632\n937\t0.646\n938\t0.811\n939\tHesitation markers (11)\n940\t0.615\n941\t0.672\n942\t0.800\n943\tAudio: emotion wav2vec2 (1024)\n944\t0.647\n945\t0.610\n946\t0.764\n947\tASR-erased time (16)\n948\t0.497\n949\t0.566\n950\t0.718\n951\tFER statistics (14)\n952\t0.529\n953\t0.551\n954\t0.669\n955\tVideo: AU/gaze (36)\n956\t0.538\n957\t0.540\n958\t0.665\n959\tVideo: VideoMAE general (768)\n960\t0.483\n961\t0.538\n962\t0.650\n963\tVideo: FER embedding (768)\n964\t0.506\n965\t0.507\n966\t0.636\n967\tAudio: HuBERT general (1024)\n968\t0.283\n969\t0.283\n970\t0.606\n971\t4.5\n972\tDoes conflict design help?\n973\tWe fix the encoders and training and vary only the cross-modal interaction\n974\t(Table\n975\t5\n976\t). The three choices land within\n977\t0.05\n978\t0.05\n979\tAP and the order\n980\tflips between splits: the orthogonal operator is best on validation but worst on test\n981\tF1, while removing conflict entirely gives the best test AP. Conflict design is not\n982\tthe lever on BAH.\n983\tTable 5:\n984\tConflict-operator ablation (public test); same model, only the conflict step\n985\tchanges.\n986\tConflict step\n987\tVal F1\n988\tTest F1\n989\tTest AP\n990\tAbsolute difference\n991\t[\n992\t2\n993\t]\n994\t0.660\n995\t0.717\n996\t0.828\n997\tOrthogonal split\n998\t0.701\n999\t0.676\n1000\t0.865\n1001\tNone\n1002\t0.683\n1003\t0.712\n1004\t0.879\n1005\t4.6\n1006\tCalibration study\n1007\tA common ensembling recipe searches member weights and re-tunes the threshold on the\n1008\tvalidation split at each step, then applies both to the test set — fitting both on\n1009\t124\n1010\t124\n1011\tvideos. This collapses\n1012\t71.7\n1013\t%\n1014\t71.7\\%\n1015\tof the weight onto a single weak member and\n1016\tscores\n1017\t0.741\n1018\t0.741\n1019\ton validation but\n1020\t0.690\n1021\t0.690\n1022\ton test (Table\n1023\t6\n1024\t, row 1).\n1025\tWeighting by AP and fixing\n1026\tτ\n1027\t=\n1028\t0.5\n1029\t\\tau=0.5\n1030\tremoves both free choices and reaches\n1031\t0.731\n1032\t0.731\n1033\t.\n1034\tNone of this is a model change. We do not oversell the margin: a paired\n1035\tbootstrap\n1036\t[\n1037\t5\n1038\t]\n1039\tplaces the gain over\n1040\t0.694\n1041\t0.694\n1042\tat\n1043\tP\n1044\t=\n1045\t0.97\n1046\tP=0.97\n1047\t, not\n1048\tcertainty.\n1049\tTable 6:\n1050\tCalibration on the public test. Fitting weights and threshold on the\n1051\t124\n1052\t124\n1053\t-video validation split loses\n1054\t4\n1055\t4\n1056\tpoints.\n1057\tRecipe\n1058\tVal F1\n1059\tTest F1\n1060\tTest AP\n1061\tSearched weights + tuned\n1062\tτ\n1063\t\\tau\n1064\t(4 mem.)\n1065\t0.741\n1066\t0.690\n1067\t0.849\n1068\tAP weights, fixed\n1069\tτ\n1070\t=\n1071\t0.5\n1072\t\\tau{=}0.5\n1073\t(5 mem.)\n1074\t—\n1075\t0.727\n1076\t0.869\n1077\tAP weights, fixed\n1078\tτ\n1079\t=\n1080\t0.5\n1081\t\\tau{=}0.5\n1082\t(6 mem.)\n1083\t—\n1084\t0.731\n1085\t0.875\n1086\t4.7\n1087\tMembers and ensemble\n1088\tTable\n1089\t7\n1090\tlists the six all-data members on the shared\n1091\t113\n1092\t113\n1093\t-video\n1094\tholdout. Adding AMF raises AP from\n1095\t0.903\n1096\t0.903\n1097\tto\n1098\t0.907\n1099\t0.907\n1100\t; its effect on holdout macro-F1\n1101\tis within retraining noise, because the five encoder members are\n1102\t0.84\n1103\t0.84\n1104\t–\n1105\t0.97\n1106\t0.97\n1107\tcorrelated and AMF is still\n1108\t0.86\n1109\t0.86\n1110\t–\n1111\t0.93\n1112\t0.93\n1113\tcorrelated with them. We keep AMF because\n1114\tthe leak-free public test favours it (Table\n1115\t3\n1116\t). On the private test the\n1117\tlocked ensemble predicts\n1118\t50.7\n1119\t%\n1120\t50.7\\%\n1121\tpositive, close to the\n1122\t54.5\n1123\t%\n1124\t54.5\\%\n1125\trate of the\n1126\tlabelled data.\n1127\tTable 7:\n1128\tAll-data members on the shared\n1129\t113\n1130\t113\n1131\t-video holdout; AP weights, fixed\n1132\tτ\n1133\t=\n1134\t0.5\n1135\t\\tau=0.5\n1136\t. The holdout serves both early stopping and weighting, so member numbers\n1137\tare mildly optimistic; the public test (Table\n1138\t3\n1139\t) is the clean evidence.\n1140\tMember\n1141\tHoldout F1\n1142\tHoldout AP\n1143\tText (RoBERTa-GoEmotions)\n1144\t0.788\n1145\t0.906\n1146\tVideo (VideoMAE)\n1147\t0.770\n1148\t0.871\n1149\tAudio (HuBERT)\n1150\t0.726\n1151\t0.831\n1152\tFusion (orthogonal)\n1153\t0.814\n1154\t0.895\n1155\tFusion (gated)\n1156\t0.805\n1157\t0.904\n1158\tAMF (ours)\n1159\t0.751\n1160\t0.900\n1161\tEnsemble, no AMF (5)\n1162\t0.823\n1163\t0.903\n1164\tEnsemble, with AMF (6)\n1165\t0.814\n1166\t0.907\n1167\t4.8\n1168\tWhat did not help?\n1169\tWe list these so others can skip them. Gaze/brow dynamics (\n1170\t36\n1171\t36\n1172\tMediaPipe\n1173\tfeatures\n1174\t[\n1175\t13\n1176\t]\n1177\t) beat the raw FER embedding on a probe but\n1178\tlowered\n1179\tthe fused model’s public-test AP (\n1180\t0.860\n1181\t→\n1182\t0.841\n1183\t0.860\\!\\rightarrow\\!0.841\n1184\t).\n1185\tProsody features (pauses, jitter, shimmer) pointed the right way but reached only AP\n1186\t0.666\n1187\t0.666\n1188\talone and hurt when fused. Supervising an extra head on BAH’s cue-type labels\n1189\tslightly lowered test AP. Swapping encoders gave no gain. Finally, none of the usual\n1190\tensemble tricks — other member subsets, rank or logit averaging, or matching the\n1191\tpredicted positive rate to the training prior (\n1192\t0.731\n1193\t→\n1194\t0.723\n1195\t0.731\\!\\rightarrow\\!0.723\n1196\t) —\n1197\tsurvived a bootstrap check. ASR-erased time is the one signal we could not yet cash\n1198\tin: as a seventh member it raises AP (\n1199\t+\n1200\t0.003\n1201\t+0.003\n1202\t) but not F1, and a stacker fit on the\n1203\tsmall validation split gives it a negative weight.\n1204\t5\n1205\tDiscussion\n1206\tWhy is the signal concentrated in text?\n1207\tBAH participants answer direct questions about their own habits, so when they feel\n1208\tconflicted they usually say so — they hedge, qualify, and contradict themselves.\n1209\tThe face and voice carry the same state far more subtly, and\n1210\t778\n1211\t778\n1212\ttraining videos\n1213\tare not enough to learn subtle cues. Every visual representation we tried, from a\n1214\tgeneric video encoder to purpose-built gaze/brow features, lands in the same narrow\n1215\tband (AP\n1216\t0.64\n1217\t0.64\n1218\t–\n1219\t0.67\n1220\t0.67\n1221\t), which reads more like a channel ceiling than a modelling\n1222\tfailure.\n1223\tWhat we would do differently?\n1224\tSet the calibration rules first and touch the model second. Quietly fitting weights\n1225\tor thresholds on the\n1226\t124\n1227\t124\n1228\t-video validation split is the most expensive mistake in\n1229\tthis line of work; it cost\n1230\t4\n1231\t4\n1232\tpoints in our own baseline and is invisible until you\n1233\ttest honestly. We would also invest in ASR-erased time earlier — it is the one\n1234\tplace where we found information the strong models demonstrably do not have.\n1235\tLimitations.\n1236\tThe public-test margin should be read with its error bars: the bootstrap interval is\n1237\t[\n1238\t0.693\n1239\t,\n1240\t0.770\n1241\t]\n1242\t[0.693,0.770]\n1243\t, so the gain over\n1244\t0.694\n1245\t0.694\n1246\tis probable but not certain. The\n1247\t113\n1248\t113\n1249\t-video holdout serves both early stopping and weighting, so its member numbers\n1250\tare mildly optimistic and small enough that AMF’s F1 contribution flips sign between\n1251\tretrainings.\n1252\t6\n1253\tConclusion\n1254\tWe studied A/H recognition on BAH and reached three conclusions that hold up under\n1255\treplication. First, cross-modal conflict\n1256\tdesign\n1257\tis not the lever: with general\n1258\tencoders two of three channels are near chance, and changing the conflict step moves\n1259\tnothing consistent. Second, features help only narrowly — emotion audio is a real\n1260\tgain, eleven interpretable markers rival a fine-tuned language model, and no facial\n1261\trepresentation rescues the video channel. Third, and most useful, calibration is the\n1262\tlargest single gain: AP weights at a fixed threshold lifted public-test macro-F1 from\n1263\t0.690\n1264\t0.690\n1265\tto\n1266\t0.731\n1267\t0.731\n1268\t, above the previous edition’s winner. Our most promising open\n1269\tdirection is ASR-erased time: the strongest and most independent non-verbal signal we\n1270\tfound, waiting for more data to convert its independence into accuracy.\n1271\tReferences\n1272\t[1]\n1273\tA. Baevski, Y. Zhou, A. Mohamed, and M. Auli\n1274\t(2020)\n1275\tWav2vec 2.0: a framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations\n1276\t.\n1277\tAdvances in neural information processing systems\n1278\t33\n1279\t,\n1280\tpp. 12449–12460\n1281\t.\n1282\tCited by:\n1283\t§3.2\n1284\t.\n1285\t[2]\n1286\tS. E. Bekhouche, H. Telli, A. Benlamoudi, S. E. Herrouz, A. Taleb-Ahmed, and A. Hadid\n1287\t(2026)\n1288\tConflict-aware multimodal fusion for ambivalence and hesitancy recognition\n1289\t.\n1290\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2603.15818\n1291\t.\n1292\tCited by:\n1293\t§1\n1294\t,\n1295\t§2\n1296\t,\n1297\t§2\n1298\t,\n1299\tTable 3\n1300\t,\n1301\tTable 3\n1302\t,\n1303\tTable 5\n1304\t.\n1305\t[3]\n1306\tD. Demszky, D. Movshovitz-Attias, J. Ko, A. Cowen, G. Nemade, and S. Ravi\n1307\t(2020)\n1308\tGoEmotions: a dataset of fine-grained emotions\n1309\t.\n1310\tIn\n1311\tProceedings of the 58th annual meeting of the association for computational linguistics\n1312\t,\n1313\tpp. 4040–4054\n1314\t.\n1315\tCited by:\n1316\t§2\n1317\t,\n1318\tTable 1\n1319\t.\n1320\t[4]\n1321\tA. Dosovitskiy, L. Beyer, A. Kolesnikov, D. Weissenborn, X. Zhai, T. Unterthiner, M. Dehghani, M. Minderer, G. Heigold, S. Gelly,\n1322\tet al.\n1323\t(2020)\n1324\tAn image is worth 16x16 words: transformers for image recognition at scale\n1325\t.\n1326\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2010.11929\n1327\t.\n1328\tCited by:\n1329\t§3.2\n1330\t.\n1331\t[5]\n1332\tB. Efron and R. J. Tibshirani\n1333\t(1994)\n1334\tAn introduction to the bootstrap\n1335\t.\n1336\tChapman and Hall/CRC\n1337\t.\n1338\tCited by:\n1339\t§4.6\n1340\t.\n1341\t[6]\n1342\tM. González-González, S. Belharbi, M. O. Zeeshan, M. Sharafi, M. H. Aslam, M. Pedersoli, A. L. Koerich, S. L. Bacon, and E. Granger\n1343\t(2025)\n1344\tBah dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for behavioural change\n1345\t.\n1346\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2505.19328\n1347\t3\n1348\t(\n1349\t9\n1350\t).\n1351\tCited by:\n1352\t§1\n1353\t,\n1354\t§2\n1355\t,\n1356\t§4.1\n1357\t,\n1358\tTable 3\n1359\t,\n1360\tTable 3\n1361\t,\n1362\tTable 3\n1363\t,\n1364\tTable 3\n1365\t.\n1366\t[7]\n1367\tC. Guo, G. Pleiss, Y. Sun, and K. Q. Weinberger\n1368\t(2017)\n1369\tOn calibration of modern neural networks\n1370\t.\n1371\tIn\n1372\tInternational Conference on Machine Learning\n1373\t,\n1374\tpp. 1321–1330\n1375\t.\n1376\tCited by:\n1377\t§2\n1378\t.\n1379\t[8]\n1380\tP. He, X. Liu, J. Gao, and W. Chen\n1381\t(2020)\n1382\tDeberta: decoding-enhanced bert with disentangled attention\n1383\t.\n1384\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2006.03654\n1385\t.\n1386\tCited by:\n1387\t§2\n1388\t.\n1389\t[9]\n1390\tW. Hsu, B. Bolte, Y. H. Tsai, K. Lakhotia, R. Salakhutdinov, and A. Mohamed\n1391\t(2021)\n1392\tHubert: self-supervised speech representation learning by masked prediction of hidden units\n1393\t.\n1394\tIEEE/ACM transactions on audio, speech, and language processing\n1395\t29\n1396\t,\n1397\tpp. 3451–3460\n1398\t.\n1399\tCited by:\n1400\t§2\n1401\t,\n1402\tTable 1\n1403\t.\n1404\t[10]\n1405\tD. Kollias, P. Tzirakis, A. Cowen, S. Zafeiriou, I. Kotsia, A. Baird, C. Gagne, C. Shao, and G. Hu\n1406\t(2024)\n1407\tThe 6th affective behavior analysis in-the-wild (abaw) competition\n1408\t.\n1409\tIn\n1410\tProceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition\n1411\t,\n1412\tpp. 4587–4598\n1413\t.\n1414\tCited by:\n1415\t§2\n1416\t.\n1417\t[11]\n1418\tY. Liu, M. Ott, N. Goyal, J. Du, M. Joshi, D. Chen, O. Levy, M. Lewis, L. Zettlemoyer, and V. Stoyanov\n1419\t(2019)\n1420\tRoberta: a robustly optimized bert pretraining approach\n1421\t.\n1422\tarXiv preprint arXiv:1907.11692\n1423\t.\n1424\tCited by:\n1425\t§2\n1426\t.\n1427\t[12]\n1428\tI. Loshchilov and F. Hutter\n1429\t(2017)\n1430\tDecoupled weight decay regularization\n1431\t.\n1432\tarXiv preprint arXiv:1711.05101\n1433\t.\n1434\tCited by:\n1435\t§4.2\n1436\t.\n1437\t[13]\n1438\tC. Lugaresi, J. Tang, H. Nash, C. McClanahan, E. Uboweja, M. Hays, F. Zhang, C. Chang, M. G. Yong, J. Lee,\n1439\tet al.\n1440\t(2019)\n1441\tMediapipe: a framework for building perception pipelines\n1442\t.\n1443\tarXiv preprint arXiv:1906.08172\n1444\t.\n1445\tCited by:\n1446\t§4.8\n1447\t.\n1448\t[14]\n1449\tA. Paszke, S. Gross, F. Massa, A. Lerer, J. Bradbury, G. Chanan, T. Killeen, Z. Lin, N. Gimelshein, L. Antiga,\n1450\tet al.\n1451\t(2019)\n1452\tPytorch: an imperative style, high-performance deep learning library\n1453\t.\n1454\tAdvances in neural information processing systems\n1455\t32\n1456\t.\n1457\tCited by:\n1458\t§4.2\n1459\t.\n1460\t[15]\n1461\tV. Pérez-Rosas, M. Abouelenien, R. Mihalcea, Y. Xiao, C. Linton, and M. Burzo\n1462\t(2015)\n1463\tVerbal and nonverbal clues for real-life deception detection\n1464\t.\n1465\tIn\n1466\tProceedings of the 2015 conference on empirical methods in natural language processing\n1467\t,\n1468\tpp. 2336–2346\n1469\t.\n1470\tCited by:\n1471\t§2\n1472\t.\n1473\t[16]\n1474\tS. Poria, E. Cambria, D. Hazarika, N. Majumder, A. Zadeh, and L. Morency\n1475\t(2017)\n1476\tContext-dependent sentiment analysis in user-generated videos\n1477\t.\n1478\tIn\n1479\tProceedings of the 55th annual meeting of the association for computational linguistics (volume 1: Long papers)\n1480\t,\n1481\tpp. 873–883\n1482\t.\n1483\tCited by:\n1484\t§2\n1485\t.\n1486\t[17]\n1487\tA. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey, and I. Sutskever\n1488\t(2023)\n1489\tRobust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision\n1490\t.\n1491\tIn\n1492\tInternational conference on machine learning\n1493\t,\n1494\tpp. 28492–28518\n1495\t.\n1496\tCited by:\n1497\t§3.4\n1498\t.\n1499\t[18]\n1500\tA. V. Savchenko\n1501\t(2025)\n1502\tHsemotion team at abaw-8 competition: audiovisual ambivalence/hesitancy, emotional mimicry intensity and facial expression recognition\n1503\t.\n1504\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2503.10399\n1505\t.\n1506\tCited by:\n1507\t§1\n1508\t.\n1509\t[19]\n1510\tC. Szegedy, V. Vanhoucke, S. Ioffe, J. Shlens, and Z. Wojna\n1511\t(2016)\n1512\tRethinking the inception architecture for computer vision\n1513\t.\n1514\tIn\n1515\tProceedings of the IEEE conference on computer vision and pattern recognition\n1516\t,\n1517\tpp. 2818–2826\n1518\t.\n1519\tCited by:\n1520\t§3.3\n1521\t,\n1522\t§4.2\n1523\t.\n1524\t[20]\n1525\tZ. Tong, Y. Song, J. Wang, and L. Wang\n1526\t(2022)\n1527\tVideomae: masked autoencoders are data-efficient learners for self-supervised video pre-training\n1528\t.\n1529\tAdvances in neural information processing systems\n1530\t35\n1531\t,\n1532\tpp. 10078–10093\n1533\t.\n1534\tCited by:\n1535\t§2\n1536\t,\n1537\tTable 1\n1538\t.\n1539\t[21]\n1540\tJ. Wagner, A. Triantafyllopoulos, H. Wierstorf, M. Schmitt, F. Burkhardt, F. Eyben, and B. W. Schuller\n1541\t(2023)\n1542\tDawn of the transformer era in speech emotion recognition: closing the valence gap\n1543\t.\n1544\tIEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence\n1545\t45\n1546\t(\n1547\t9\n1548\t),\n1549\tpp. 10745–10759\n1550\t.\n1551\tCited by:\n1552\t§2\n1553\t,\n1554\t§3.2\n1555\t,\n1556\tTable 1\n1557\t.\n1558\t[22]\n1559\tT. Wolf, L. Debut, V. Sanh, J. Chaumond, C. Delangue, A. Moi, P. Cistac, T. Rault, R. Louf, M. Funtowicz,\n1560\tet al.\n1561\t(2020)\n1562\tTransformers: state-of-the-art natural language processing\n1563\t.\n1564\tIn\n1565\tProceedings of the 2020 Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Processing: System Demonstrations\n1566\t,\n1567\tpp. 38–45\n1568\t.\n1569\tCited by:\n1570\t§4.2\n1571\t.\n1572\t[23]\n1573\tL. Wu, J. Li, Y. Wang, Q. Meng, T. Qin, W. Chen, M. Zhang, T. Liu,\n1574\tet al.\n1575\t(2021)\n1576\tR-drop: regularized dropout for neural networks\n1577\t.\n1578\tAdvances in neural information processing systems\n1579\t34\n1580\t,\n1581\tpp. 10890–10905\n1582\t.\n1583\tCited by:\n1584\t§4.2\n1585\t.\n1586\tExperimental support, please\n1587\tview the build logs\n1588\tfor errors. Generated by\n1589\tL\n1590\tA\n1591\tT\n1592\tE\n1593\txml\n1594\t.\n1595\tInstructions for reporting errors\n1596\tWe are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile\n1597\t      support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the\n1598\t      methods listed below:\n1599\tClick the \"Report Issue\"\n1600\t(\n1601\t)\n1602\tbutton, located in the page header.\n1603\tTip:\n1604\tYou can select the relevant text first, to include it in your report.\n1605\tOur team has already identified\n1606\tthe following issues\n1607\t. We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we\n1608\t      may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability\n1609\t      should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for\n1610\t      all.\n1611\tHave a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTeXML maintain a\n1612\tlist of packages that need conversion\n1613\t, and welcome\n1614\tdeveloper contributions\n1615\t.\n1616\tWe gratefully acknowledge support from\n1617\t        our\n1618\tmajor funders\n1619\t,\n1620\tmember institutions\n1621\t,\n1622\t,\n1623\t        and all contributors.\n1624\tMajor funding support from\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b1004a4d-e758-43e1-9f76-0588590cf162", "uuid": "6562a363-8fef-40d6-a5f7-530b2f38c5b1", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T05:58:29.936Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_text.txt", "content": "Simple Features and Honest Calibration for Ambivalence and Hesitancy Recognition in Video\nReport GitHub Issue\n×\nTitle:\nContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\nDescription:\nSubmit without GitHub\nSubmit in GitHub\narXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\nLearn more\n×\nBack to arXiv\nLicense: CC BY 4.0\narXiv:2607.11120v1 [cs.CV] 13 Jul 2026\nSimple Features and Honest Calibration for\nAmbivalence and Hesitancy Recognition in Video\nVikas Kumar\nIndian Institute of Science Education and Research Bhopal, India\nvikas25@iiserb.ac.in\nAditya Mishra\nIndian Institute of Science Education and Research Bhopal, India\naditya21@iiserb.ac.in\nHaroon R. Lone\nIndian Institute of Science Education and Research Bhopal, India\nharoon@iiserb.ac.in\nAbstract\nWe address ambivalence and hesitancy (A/H) recognition in the ABAW 2026 BAH\nChallenge: given a short interview video, predict whether the person shows signs\nof A/H. Our system combines affect-specialised text, audio, and visual\nrepresentations with a small set of readable linguistic hesitation cues, fused by\na reliability gate we call Affective Marker Fusion (AMF), and finished with a\nsimple AP-weighted ensemble at a fixed decision threshold. We also introduce\nASR-erased time\n: speech recognisers delete fillers and hesitation pauses\nfrom the transcript, but the chunk timestamps keep the time those events took, and\nsixteen features built from these gaps form the strongest and most independent\nnon-verbal channel we measured (AP\n0.718\n0.718\n, correlation\n0.11\n0.11\n–\n0.36\n0.36\nwith all\nother members). Across controlled experiments we find three things: cross-modal\nconflict design does not reliably help on BAH; language is by far the strongest\nchannel while affect-specialised audio is a useful second; and calibration matters\nmore than architecture. Fitting ensemble weights and a threshold on the small validation split overfits: it scores\n0.741\n0.741\nmacro-F1 on validation but only\n0.690\n0.690\non the untouched test set. AP-weighting at a fixed threshold instead reaches\n0.731\n\\mathbf{0.731}\non test.\nThe full pipeline is deterministic and runs from one script.\n1\n1\n1\nCode:\nhttps://github.com/wmivikas/ABAW2026-Task2-ECCV\n.\n1\nIntroduction\nAmbivalence and hesitancy (A/H) are states of internal conflict: a person is unsure,\nor pulled two ways at once. Detecting these moments in short answer videos is useful\nfor behaviour-change tools, where a moment of hesitation is a good time to\nintervene. The ABAW 2026 challenge frames this as a binary, video-level task on the\nBAH dataset\n[\n6\n]\n, scored by macro-F1 (the unweighted mean of the\npresent- and absent-class F1) with average precision (AP) as a secondary measure.\nA/H is widely treated as a\ncross-modal conflict\nproblem, and the strongest\nprior systems build hand-designed conflict features on top of three pre-trained\nencoders\n[\n2\n,\n18\n]\n. We reproduce that\nrecipe, test its central claim, and then ask a simpler question: where is the signal\nactually? Three results organise the paper.\n1.\nConflict design is not the lever.\nWith encoders and training fixed,\nswapping the conflict operator (absolute difference, orthogonal split, or none)\nmoves public-test AP by at most\n0.05\n0.05\nand does not order the same way on validation\nand test (Sec.\n4.5\n).\n2.\nFeatures help, but narrowly.\nWith general encoders the video and audio\nchannels are near chance. An emotion-specialised audio encoder is a real gain; no\nfacial representation we tried rescues the video channel (Sec.\n4.4\n).\nCalibration is the biggest gain.\nOn\n778\n778\ntraining videos, fitting ensemble weights and the decision threshold on the\n124\n124\n-video validation split scores\n0.741\n0.741\nthere but only\n0.690\n0.690\non test — the classic overfitting signature. Removing that search and using AP weights at a fixed threshold lifts public-test macro-F1 to\n0.731\n0.731\n(Sec.\n4.6\n).\nContributions.\n•\nAMF\n, a compact reliability-gated fusion of affect-specialised streams\nand eleven interpretable hesitation markers.\n•\nASR-erased time\n, a new\n16\n16\n-dimensional signal recovered from ASR\nchunk timestamps; it is the strongest non-verbal channel on BAH and nearly\nuncorrelated with every model member.\n•\nA controlled study showing that conflict design does not help, that the signal\nis concentrated in language, and that AP-weighted calibration at a fixed threshold\nis the single largest source of improvement.\n•\nA deterministic, one-command pipeline that reaches\n0.731\n0.731\nmacro-F1 on the\npublic test, above the previous edition’s winner.\nFigure 1:\nOverview. Text, video, and audio inputs are turned into affect-specialised\nfeatures. AMF gates weak channels and predicts A/H. Six members are combined by\nAP-weighted averaging at a fixed threshold of\n0.5\n0.5\n. Features that hurt the model\n(gaze/brow dynamics, prosody, cue supervision) are excluded.\n2\nRelated Work\nABAW and BAH.\nThe ABAW series benchmarks multimodal affect in\nvideo\n[\n10\n]\n. BAH\n[\n6\n]\nadds whole-video A/H labels\nwith transcripts, aligned faces, and per-segment cue tags. The organisers’ zero-shot\nLLM baseline reaches\n0.283\n0.283\nmacro-F1 and their co-attention baseline\n0.59\n0.59\n; the\nprevious edition’s winner reports\n0.694\n0.694\npublic /\n0.715\n0.715\nprivate\n[\n2\n]\n.\nConflict fusion.\nPrior A/H systems encode conflict as element-wise\nabsolute differences between encoder features\n[\n2\n]\n, echoing\ndisagreement-aware fusion in multimodal sentiment analysis\n[\n16\n]\nand cross-modal mismatch modelling in deception\ndetection\n[\n15\n]\n. We ask whether this helps once the\nencoders are fixed, and find it does not reliably help on BAH.\nGeneral vs. affect-specialised encoders.\nPrior work uses VideoMAE,\npre-trained for actions\n[\n20\n]\n, and HuBERT, general\nspeech\n[\n9\n]\n. Neither targets facial or vocal emotion. We substitute a\nfacial-expression model and an emotion speech model\n[\n21\n]\n; only the\naudio substitution pays off. For text we use RoBERTa\n[\n11\n]\nfine-tuned on\nGoEmotions\n[\n3\n]\n, whose emotion labels (confusion,\nnervousness) fit hesitancy; a larger general model (DeBERTa-v3-large\n[\n8\n]\n)\nwas worse, so the right pre-training beats scale.\nInterpretable hesitation cues.\nHesitancy has well-studied linguistic\ncorrelates: hedges, filled pauses, self-repairs, contrastive markers. We compile\nthese into a short, readable vector that rivals a fine-tuned language model.\nCalibration on small data.\nWith\n778\n778\ntraining videos the macro-F1\nthreshold is high-variance; poor calibration is a known failure mode of modern\nnetworks\n[\n7\n]\n. We show that tuning the threshold on the\n124\n124\n-video validation split does not transfer, and instead fix it and weight members\nby AP, which is threshold-free.\n3\nMethod\n3.1\nProblem formulation\nEach video\nx\nx\nhas a binary label\ny\n∈\n{\n0\n,\n1\n}\ny\\in\\{0,1\\}\nand an elicitation question\nq\n∈\n{\n1\n,\n…\n,\n7\n}\nq\\in\\{1,\\dots,7\\}\n. We predict a probability\np\n​\n(\ny\n=\n1\n∣\nx\n)\np(y{=}1\\mid x)\nand are scored by\nmacro-F1\n=\n1\n2\n​\n(\nF\n1\n(\n0\n)\n+\nF\n1\n(\n1\n)\n)\n\\text{macro-F1}=\\tfrac{1}{2}(F_{1}^{(0)}+F_{1}^{(1)})\n, with positive-class AP as a\nsecondary measure.\n3.2\nModality encoders\nWe use frozen affect-oriented encoders (Table\n1\n). Text is the\nRoBERTa-GoEmotions sentence embedding; video is a facial-expression ViT\n[\n4\n]\nover\n16\n16\naligned face frames, giving an embedding and a\n7\n7\n-way expression profile\n(mean and standard deviation); audio is an emotion-fine-tuned\nwav2vec2\n[\n1\n]\nmodel\n[\n21\n]\n, mean-pooled over time. We additionally compute eleven interpretable text markers: rates of hedges,\nfilled pauses, contrastive (“but”-type) words, negations, first-person uncertainty,\nrepeated words, and how much sentiment flips within the answer.\nTable 1:\nEncoders. All are frozen; only lightweight heads are trained.\nStream\nBackbone\nDim\nText\nRoBERTa-GoEmotions\n[\n3\n]\n768\nText markers\nhand-crafted hesitation cues\n11\nVideo\nFER-ViT (facial expression)\n768 + 14\nAudio\nemotion wav2vec2\n[\n21\n]\n1024\nEncoder members (separate) also use:\nVideo (enc.)\nVideoMAE-Base\n[\n20\n]\n768\nAudio (enc.)\nHuBERT-Large\n[\n9\n]\n1024\n3.3\nAffective Marker Fusion (AMF)\nEach stream\ns\n∈\n{\ntext\n,\nvideo\n,\naudio\n,\nmarkers\n}\ns\\in\\{\\text{text},\\text{video},\\text{audio},\\text{markers}\\}\nis\nprojected to a shared width,\nh\ns\n=\nϕ\ns\n​\n(\nf\ns\n)\nh_{s}=\\phi_{s}(f_{s})\n. A learned gate assigns each stream a\nreliability weight, so weak channels are turned down rather than added as noise:\ng\n=\nσ\n​\n(\nW\n​\n[\nh\nt\n;\nh\nv\n;\nh\na\n;\nh\nm\n]\n)\n∈\n(\n0\n,\n1\n)\n4\n,\nh\n~\ns\n=\ng\ns\n​\nh\ns\n.\ng=\\sigma\\!\\big(W[h_{\\text{t}};h_{\\text{v}};h_{\\text{a}};h_{\\text{m}}]\\big)\\in(0,1)^{4},\\qquad\\tilde{h}_{s}=g_{s}\\,h_{s}.\n(1)\nThe gated streams and a question embedding are concatenated and passed to a small\nMLP. An auxiliary head predicts A/H from the markers alone, which regularises the\nshared representation and exposes an interpretable sub-decision. We minimise a class-balanced binary cross-entropy loss with label smoothing,\nℒ\n=\nBCE\n​\nw\n​\n(\np\n,\ny\n~\n)\n+\n0.3\n⋅\nBCE\n​\nw\n​\n(\np\n​\nmarker\n,\ny\n)\n,\n\\mathcal{L}=\\mathrm{BCE}w\\big(p,\\tilde{y}\\big)+0.3\\cdot\\mathrm{BCE}w\\big(p{\\text{marker}},y\\big),\n(2)\nwhere\nBCE\n​\nw\n​\n(\np\n,\ny\n)\n=\n−\n,\nw\n,\ny\n​\nlog\n⁡\np\n−\n(\n1\n−\ny\n)\n​\nlog\n⁡\n(\n1\n−\np\n)\n\\mathrm{BCE}w(p,y)=-,w,y\\log p-(1-y)\\log(1-p)\n,\nw\n=\n(\nN\n−\nN\n+\n)\n/\nN\n+\nw=(N{-}N{+})/N{+}\nre-weights the positive class by its inverse frequency, and\ny\n~\n=\ny\n​\n(\n1\n−\nϵ\n)\n+\nϵ\n/\n2\n\\tilde{y}=y(1-\\epsilon)+\\epsilon/2\nis the smoothed label (\nϵ\n=\n0.1\n\\epsilon=0.1\n). We use the standard smoothing value\n[\n19\n]\nrather than tuning it, since\n778\n778\ntraining videos and noisy labels are exactly the setting label smoothing is meant to guard against overconfidence in. The marker-head weight of\n0.3\n0.3\nis kept low enough that this auxiliary loss regularises the shared representation without dominating the main objective, while still forcing the\n25\n25\n-dim marker pathway to stay independently predictive.\n3.4\nASR-erased time\nSpeech recognisers are trained to output\nclean\ntext: they delete fillers\n(“um”, “uh”), restarts, and hesitation pauses. In BAH, only\n7\n%\n7\\%\nof the Whisper\n[\n17\n]\ntranscripts contain any filler word. But the transcripts carry per-chunk timestamps,\nand time cannot be deleted: when the recogniser drops a filled pause, the gap it\noccupied remains between the end of one chunk and the start of the next. We recover\nsixteen deterministic features from these gaps: gap counts and sizes normalised by\nspeech time, within-chunk speaking rate and its variability, chunk fragmentation,\nthe gap immediately before a contrast word (the pause-then-qualify pattern), and\nrestarts across chunk borders. Whisper timestamps reset every\n30\n30\ns, so gaps are\ncounted only where the timeline is monotone.\n3.5\nEnsemble and calibration\nWe combine\nM\nM\nmembers by AP-weighted probability averaging and a\nfixed\nthreshold\nτ\n=\n0.5\n\\tau=0.5\n:\np\n¯\n​\n(\nx\n)\n=\n∑\nm\nw\nm\n​\np\nm\n​\n(\nx\n)\n,\nw\nm\n=\nAP\nm\n∑\nm\n′\nAP\nm\n′\n.\n\\bar{p}(x)=\\sum_{m}w_{m}\\,p_{m}(x),\\qquad w_{m}=\\frac{\\mathrm{AP}_{m}}{\\sum_{m^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{AP}_{m^{\\prime}}}.\n(3)\nAP is threshold-free and therefore stable on small data. Fixing\nτ\n\\tau\nis deliberate:\nSec.\n4.6\nshows a validation-tuned threshold does not transfer.\n3.6\nTraining on all labelled data\nThe rules permit training on all labelled data, and with only\n778\n778\ntraining videos to begin with, using the additional val/test videos should only help the final model. For the final model we pool train+val+test (\n1427\n1427\nvideos). Since no split remains for early stopping, we carve a seeded stratified holdout of\n113\n113\nvideos (\n8\n%\n8\\%\n) — chosen to match the proportion of the original validation split (\n124\n/\n1427\n≈\n8.7\n%\n124/1427\\approx 8.7\\%\n), so the stopping signal is exactly as reliable as before while training sees far more data. We fit the ensemble weights on this holdout and keep\nτ\n=\n0.5\n\\tau=0.5\n, the same fixed, untuned threshold justified in Sec.\n4.6\n. Two invariants keep this clean, both enforced in code: every member holds out the\nsame\n113\n113\nvideos from one shared function, so no member is scored on a video it trained on; and the training and inference paths are asserted to return identical probabilities for a saved checkpoint.\n4\nExperiments\n4.1\nDataset\nBAH\n[\n6\n]\ncontains\n1427\n1427\nlabelled videos from\n300\n300\nparticipants,\nsplit participant-wise (Table\n2\n); no person appears in two splits. There\nis also a private test of\n152\n152\nvideos from\n30\n30\nfurther participants, released\nunlabelled: we predict on it but cannot score it, and the organisers rank the\nsubmitted files (up to five trials). Every number we report is measured on the\nlabelled public test (\n525\n525\nvideos, for models trained on the training split) or on\nthe shared\n113\n113\n-video holdout (for the all-data models); we never mix the two.\nTable 2:\nBAH split statistics (participant-wise).\nSplit\nVideos\nA/H (+)\nNo A/H (\n−\n-\n)\nTrain\n778\n385 (49%)\n393 (51%)\nValidation\n124\n75 (60%)\n49 (40%)\nPublic test\n525\n318 (61%)\n207 (39%)\nPrivate test\n152\n—\n—\n4.2\nImplementation details\nAll models are trained on a single NVIDIA RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell Workstation Edition GPU. The encoders are frozen, and lightweight heads are optimized using AdamW\n[\n12\n]\n, label smoothing\n[\n19\n]\n0.1\n0.1\n, and early stopping (patience\n15\n15\n). The\ntext head uses learning rate\n2\n×\n10\n−\n5\n2\\!\\times\\!10^{-5}\nand R-Drop\n[\n23\n]\n; the\nvideo, audio, and fusion heads use\n1\n×\n10\n−\n4\n1\\!\\times\\!10^{-4}\n; AMF uses a shared width of\n256\n256\nand marker-head weight\n0.3\n0.3\n. We implement everything in\nPyTorch\n[\n14\n]\nwith the Transformers library\n[\n22\n]\n. Ensemble weights come from Eq.\n3\nand the\nthreshold is fixed at\n0.5\n0.5\n. Training is deterministic within a fixed\nsoftware/hardware state; across sessions individual members can drift by up to about\na point of F1 (GPU numerics), while the ensemble is stable to\n±\n0.0001\n\\pm 0.0001\n.\n4.3\nMain results\nTable\n3\ncompares our system with published BAH results. A single AMF\nmember already exceeds the strongest BAH baseline, and the AP-weighted six-member\nensemble reaches\n0.731\n0.731\nmacro-F1 on the public test, above the previous edition’s\nwinner (\n0.694\n0.694\n). A paired bootstrap over the\n525\n525\ntest videos gives a\n95\n%\n95\\%\ninterval of\n[\n0.693\n,\n0.770\n]\n[0.693,0.770]\nand\nP\n​\n(\nours\n>\n0.694\n)\n=\n0.97\nP(\\text{ours}>0.694)=0.97\n.\nTable 3:\nPublic-test comparison (\n525\n525\nvideos). Baselines from\n[\n6\n]\n;\nprevious winner from\n[\n2\n]\n.\nMethod\nMacro-F1\nZero-shot M-LLM (vision only)\n[\n6\n]\n0.283\nLFAN co-attention (V+A+T)\n[\n6\n]\n0.590\nZero-shot M-LLM + transcript\n[\n6\n]\n0.634\nConflictAwareAH\n[\n2\n]\n0.694\nOurs: AMF single member\n0.725\nOurs: 6-member AP-weighted ensemble\n0.731\n4.4\nWhere the signal is?\nWe fit a logistic probe on each frozen feature stream, all at a fixed threshold of\n0.5\n0.5\n(Table\n4\n). Text is strongest (AP\n0.811\n0.811\n), and eleven\nhesitation markers nearly match it (AP\n0.800\n0.800\n). The emotion audio encoder is far\nabove general HuBERT (AP\n0.764\n0.764\nvs.\n0.606\n0.606\n; frozen HuBERT collapses to one class\nat\nτ\n=\n0.5\n\\tau=0.5\n). ASR-erased time reaches AP\n0.718\n0.718\n— above every face and\ngeneral-audio feature — and its predictions correlate only\n0.11\n0.11\n–\n0.36\n0.36\nwith the\nsix model members, far below anything else we measured. Every visual representation\nstays weak, including purpose-built gaze/brow dynamics.\nTable 4:\nPer-stream logistic probe, fixed threshold\n0.5\n0.5\n.\nFeature stream\nVal F1\nTest F1\nTest AP\nText: RoBERTa-GoEmotions (768)\n0.632\n0.646\n0.811\nHesitation markers (11)\n0.615\n0.672\n0.800\nAudio: emotion wav2vec2 (1024)\n0.647\n0.610\n0.764\nASR-erased time (16)\n0.497\n0.566\n0.718\nFER statistics (14)\n0.529\n0.551\n0.669\nVideo: AU/gaze (36)\n0.538\n0.540\n0.665\nVideo: VideoMAE general (768)\n0.483\n0.538\n0.650\nVideo: FER embedding (768)\n0.506\n0.507\n0.636\nAudio: HuBERT general (1024)\n0.283\n0.283\n0.606\n4.5\nDoes conflict design help?\nWe fix the encoders and training and vary only the cross-modal interaction\n(Table\n5\n). The three choices land within\n0.05\n0.05\nAP and the order\nflips between splits: the orthogonal operator is best on validation but worst on test\nF1, while removing conflict entirely gives the best test AP. Conflict design is not\nthe lever on BAH.\nTable 5:\nConflict-operator ablation (public test); same model, only the conflict step\nchanges.\nConflict step\nVal F1\nTest F1\nTest AP\nAbsolute difference\n[\n2\n]\n0.660\n0.717\n0.828\nOrthogonal split\n0.701\n0.676\n0.865\nNone\n0.683\n0.712\n0.879\n4.6\nCalibration study\nA common ensembling recipe searches member weights and re-tunes the threshold on the\nvalidation split at each step, then applies both to the test set — fitting both on\n124\n124\nvideos. This collapses\n71.7\n%\n71.7\\%\nof the weight onto a single weak member and\nscores\n0.741\n0.741\non validation but\n0.690\n0.690\non test (Table\n6\n, row 1).\nWeighting by AP and fixing\nτ\n=\n0.5\n\\tau=0.5\nremoves both free choices and reaches\n0.731\n0.731\n.\nNone of this is a model change. We do not oversell the margin: a paired\nbootstrap\n[\n5\n]\nplaces the gain over\n0.694\n0.694\nat\nP\n=\n0.97\nP=0.97\n, not\ncertainty.\nTable 6:\nCalibration on the public test. Fitting weights and threshold on the\n124\n124\n-video validation split loses\n4\n4\npoints.\nRecipe\nVal F1\nTest F1\nTest AP\nSearched weights + tuned\nτ\n\\tau\n(4 mem.)\n0.741\n0.690\n0.849\nAP weights, fixed\nτ\n=\n0.5\n\\tau{=}0.5\n(5 mem.)\n—\n0.727\n0.869\nAP weights, fixed\nτ\n=\n0.5\n\\tau{=}0.5\n(6 mem.)\n—\n0.731\n0.875\n4.7\nMembers and ensemble\nTable\n7\nlists the six all-data members on the shared\n113\n113\n-video\nholdout. Adding AMF raises AP from\n0.903\n0.903\nto\n0.907\n0.907\n; its effect on holdout macro-F1\nis within retraining noise, because the five encoder members are\n0.84\n0.84\n–\n0.97\n0.97\ncorrelated and AMF is still\n0.86\n0.86\n–\n0.93\n0.93\ncorrelated with them. We keep AMF because\nthe leak-free public test favours it (Table\n3\n). On the private test the\nlocked ensemble predicts\n50.7\n%\n50.7\\%\npositive, close to the\n54.5\n%\n54.5\\%\nrate of the\nlabelled data.\nTable 7:\nAll-data members on the shared\n113\n113\n-video holdout; AP weights, fixed\nτ\n=\n0.5\n\\tau=0.5\n. The holdout serves both early stopping and weighting, so member numbers\nare mildly optimistic; the public test (Table\n3\n) is the clean evidence.\nMember\nHoldout F1\nHoldout AP\nText (RoBERTa-GoEmotions)\n0.788\n0.906\nVideo (VideoMAE)\n0.770\n0.871\nAudio (HuBERT)\n0.726\n0.831\nFusion (orthogonal)\n0.814\n0.895\nFusion (gated)\n0.805\n0.904\nAMF (ours)\n0.751\n0.900\nEnsemble, no AMF (5)\n0.823\n0.903\nEnsemble, with AMF (6)\n0.814\n0.907\n4.8\nWhat did not help?\nWe list these so others can skip them. Gaze/brow dynamics (\n36\n36\nMediaPipe\nfeatures\n[\n13\n]\n) beat the raw FER embedding on a probe but\nlowered\nthe fused model’s public-test AP (\n0.860\n→\n0.841\n0.860\\!\\rightarrow\\!0.841\n).\nProsody features (pauses, jitter, shimmer) pointed the right way but reached only AP\n0.666\n0.666\nalone and hurt when fused. Supervising an extra head on BAH’s cue-type labels\nslightly lowered test AP. Swapping encoders gave no gain. Finally, none of the usual\nensemble tricks — other member subsets, rank or logit averaging, or matching the\npredicted positive rate to the training prior (\n0.731\n→\n0.723\n0.731\\!\\rightarrow\\!0.723\n) —\nsurvived a bootstrap check. ASR-erased time is the one signal we could not yet cash\nin: as a seventh member it raises AP (\n+\n0.003\n+0.003\n) but not F1, and a stacker fit on the\nsmall validation split gives it a negative weight.\n5\nDiscussion\nWhy is the signal concentrated in text?\nBAH participants answer direct questions about their own habits, so when they feel\nconflicted they usually say so — they hedge, qualify, and contradict themselves.\nThe face and voice carry the same state far more subtly, and\n778\n778\ntraining videos\nare not enough to learn subtle cues. Every visual representation we tried, from a\ngeneric video encoder to purpose-built gaze/brow features, lands in the same narrow\nband (AP\n0.64\n0.64\n–\n0.67\n0.67\n), which reads more like a channel ceiling than a modelling\nfailure.\nWhat we would do differently?\nSet the calibration rules first and touch the model second. Quietly fitting weights\nor thresholds on the\n124\n124\n-video validation split is the most expensive mistake in\nthis line of work; it cost\n4\n4\npoints in our own baseline and is invisible until you\ntest honestly. We would also invest in ASR-erased time earlier — it is the one\nplace where we found information the strong models demonstrably do not have.\nLimitations.\nThe public-test margin should be read with its error bars: the bootstrap interval is\n[\n0.693\n,\n0.770\n]\n[0.693,0.770]\n, so the gain over\n0.694\n0.694\nis probable but not certain. The\n113\n113\n-video holdout serves both early stopping and weighting, so its member numbers\nare mildly optimistic and small enough that AMF’s F1 contribution flips sign between\nretrainings.\n6\nConclusion\nWe studied A/H recognition on BAH and reached three conclusions that hold up under\nreplication. First, cross-modal conflict\ndesign\nis not the lever: with general\nencoders two of three channels are near chance, and changing the conflict step moves\nnothing consistent. Second, features help only narrowly — emotion audio is a real\ngain, eleven interpretable markers rival a fine-tuned language model, and no facial\nrepresentation rescues the video channel. Third, and most useful, calibration is the\nlargest single gain: AP weights at a fixed threshold lifted public-test macro-F1 from\n0.690\n0.690\nto\n0.731\n0.731\n, above the previous edition’s winner. Our most promising open\ndirection is ASR-erased time: the strongest and most independent non-verbal signal we\nfound, waiting for more data to convert its independence into accuracy.\nReferences\n[1]\nA. Baevski, Y. Zhou, A. Mohamed, and M. Auli\n(2020)\nWav2vec 2.0: a framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations\n.\nAdvances in neural information processing systems\n33\n,\npp. 12449–12460\n.\nCited by:\n§3.2\n.\n[2]\nS. E. Bekhouche, H. Telli, A. Benlamoudi, S. E. Herrouz, A. Taleb-Ahmed, and A. Hadid\n(2026)\nConflict-aware multimodal fusion for ambivalence and hesitancy recognition\n.\narXiv preprint arXiv:2603.15818\n.\nCited by:\n§1\n,\n§2\n,\n§2\n,\nTable 3\n,\nTable 3\n,\nTable 5\n.\n[3]\nD. Demszky, D. Movshovitz-Attias, J. Ko, A. Cowen, G. Nemade, and S. Ravi\n(2020)\nGoEmotions: a dataset of fine-grained emotions\n.\nIn\nProceedings of the 58th annual meeting of the association for computational linguistics\n,\npp. 4040–4054\n.\nCited by:\n§2\n,\nTable 1\n.\n[4]\nA. Dosovitskiy, L. Beyer, A. Kolesnikov, D. Weissenborn, X. Zhai, T. Unterthiner, M. Dehghani, M. Minderer, G. Heigold, S. Gelly,\net al.\n(2020)\nAn image is worth 16x16 words: transformers for image recognition at scale\n.\narXiv preprint arXiv:2010.11929\n.\nCited by:\n§3.2\n.\n[5]\nB. Efron and R. J. Tibshirani\n(1994)\nAn introduction to the bootstrap\n.\nChapman and Hall/CRC\n.\nCited by:\n§4.6\n.\n[6]\nM. González-González, S. Belharbi, M. O. Zeeshan, M. Sharafi, M. H. Aslam, M. Pedersoli, A. L. Koerich, S. L. Bacon, and E. Granger\n(2025)\nBah dataset for ambivalence/hesitancy recognition in videos for behavioural change\n.\narXiv preprint arXiv:2505.19328\n3\n(\n9\n).\nCited by:\n§1\n,\n§2\n,\n§4.1\n,\nTable 3\n,\nTable 3\n,\nTable 3\n,\nTable 3\n.\n[7]\nC. Guo, G. Pleiss, Y. Sun, and K. Q. Weinberger\n(2017)\nOn calibration of modern neural networks\n.\nIn\nInternational Conference on Machine Learning\n,\npp. 1321–1330\n.\nCited by:\n§2\n.\n[8]\nP. He, X. Liu, J. Gao, and W. Chen\n(2020)\nDeberta: decoding-enhanced bert with disentangled attention\n.\narXiv pr